##AN IDEA FROM CHATGPT ##
# Your list of values
value_list="rufa aqu1"

# Filter the lines in the table file based on the list
filtered_lines=$(grep -F -w -f <(echo "$value_list" | tr ' ' '\n') table.txt)

# Preserve the original order using awk
awk 'NR==FNR{a[$0];next}($1 in a)' <(echo "$filtered_lines") table.txt

Here's how this script works:

    The tr command is used to convert the space-separated list of values into a newline-separated list for grep to process.

    grep -F -w -f is used to search for lines in "table.txt" that match the values in the list. -F treats the search patterns as fixed strings (no regex), -w matches whole words, and -f reads the patterns from the input file.

    The result of the grep command is stored in the filtered_lines variable.

    The awk command is used to preserve the original order. It compares each line of the original table file ("table.txt") with the lines in filtered_lines and prints the matching lines.

This will give you the lines from "table.txt" that match the values in your list while preserving their original order.
## THE CHATGPT IDEA ENDS HERE ##

